WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
[Amit Varma]: I like reading mythology, and one reason for that is that I like funky monsters.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a centaur, half-human and half-horse.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a kraken, a giant squid or octopus or a primeval form of Thulu.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a manticore with the head of a human, the body of a lion and the tail of a scorpion.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a basilisk, a giant reptile that can kill you with a single glance.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a rock arosi, a giant predatory bird known for picking up elephants from the ground,

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
[Amit Varma]: dropping them from a height and feasting on the carcass.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Fun creatures, all of them.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And hey, all our mythologies and all our monsters are not from the past.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a modern monster who can see into the future,

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
[Amit Varma]: who plays something called the infinite game and who gives birth to unicorns.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
[Amit Varma]: All hail the venture capitalist.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badman.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
[Amit Varma]: My subject for today is a world of venture capital in India.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
[Amit Varma]: But as you would expect, it's actually much broader than that.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Good venture capitalists need to have an understanding of the society in which they live.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Not just at one moment in time, but how it is evolving.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
[Amit Varma]: They need to have a sense of the human condition, our needs and desires and our problems that need solving.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
[Amit Varma]: They need to be able to peer into the future and then they need to put their money where their mouth is.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:44.000
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me that a good venture capitalist needs to be intellectually curious, empathetic and optimistic.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: My guest today to talk about all this and more is Sajith Pai, a director at Bloom Ventures,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: who spent a couple of decades in media, most of that time in the Times of India,

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
[Amit Varma]: before making a leap to venture capital.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Sajith is a prolific essayist and some of his think pieces have caused a fundamental shift

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: in the way that people think about this industry and perhaps this country.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.000
[Amit Varma]: So my discussion with Sajith spanned much more than his investment philosophy or the startup scene here.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure you'll find it insightful as well.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to the conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

