[Amit Varma]: Why should only machines do the learning?

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Sajith, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you very much. Thank you for having me.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
[Amit Varma]: So you've had for someone who's a venture capitalist, you've had an atypical and interesting journey.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
[Amit Varma]: You have described yourself in the past as an accidental VC, which is interesting because I've had other guests

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
[Amit Varma]: who've called themselves accidental crusaders and accidental reformers and all of that.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit more about you, your background.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
[Amit Varma]: What were your sort of interests as a young person? And tell me a little bit about your journey.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
[Guest]: I grew up in Kerala and sort of had this not exactly peripatetic,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.000
[Guest]: but there was a fair amount of, you know, transfers, et cetera, because my father was in the central bank.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
[Guest]: I ended up doing my undergrad from Goa.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:29.000
[Guest]: And of course, the Goa of college in the 90s is very different from the Goa of the beaches.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:36.000
[Guest]: And then ended up doing an MBA from Miami and then joined the Times of India group and worked there for a fairly long time.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.000
[Guest]: And I think one reason I ended up working there was also an interesting place,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:47.000
[Guest]: because all the conversations were really, really interesting. Got to talk with a diverse set of people.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
[Guest]: And for a business guy, I was always on the business side. I got along very well with the edit guys.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Guest]: And I ended up working there for a long time across multiple kind of roles, broadly in the strategy,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
[Guest]: best to have started a few businesses. And in fact, the most interesting one was, of course,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Guest]: Times Now was supposed to be called ETTV then. And Partho and I, Partho sadly now is in prison.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
[Guest]: Anyway, so Partho and I were the first employees, so to say, we got transferred from the Economic Times.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
[Guest]: And then Arunabh Goswami was employee number five.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:29.000
[Guest]: And I of course moved out and briefly to work in another media company where Prakash Iyer was my boss.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:36.000
[Guest]: And after about a couple of years, I joined the Times Pack. And I was there for another 10 years.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
[Guest]: And so coincidentally, the division that I joined Times Pack was a division called Brand Capital,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest]: which was headed by Karthik Reddy. Not exactly headed, but he was one of the senior guys there.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
[Guest]: And as it so happened, he moved out two years to start Bloom Ventures, which is an early stage venture firm.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest]: And in 2018, I was really getting bored and I kind of made up my mind to quit.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest]: Fortunately, I got a call from him and he said, look, what are you doing, et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.000
[Guest]: There is a role. Would you be interested? And I'm like, wow, of course.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, I'm giving you kind of my timeline, really, so to say.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: But what it doesn't really tell you is kind of and you know that I quiz.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:21.000
[Guest]: And so I've always had this interest in trivia, fairly Catholic interests, very diverse interests,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Guest]: and obsessed by lots of little things. And to that extent, I think I bring in that journalist perspective.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:35.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think I could probably run a division as well as some of the founders I kind of invested to.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Guest]: But it does give me a kind of perspective, a worldview, and that serves me well in this business.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.000
[Guest]: So that's kind of a little bit about me. I now find myself, interestingly enough, in Delhi.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:52.000
[Guest]: And the funny thing is that I lived in Bandra in Bombay for about 14 years.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
[Guest]: And then there's an interesting opportunity to start a university business for the times.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:01.000
[Guest]: And I leapt at it and ended up finding myself in Noida because the university was in Greater Noida.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:07.000
[Guest]: And the interesting thing is, I remember going to get my Candra Bank account kind of shifted.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:13.000
[Guest]: And so the previous one was in Bandra and this one was in a small village called Bangal nearby.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
[Guest]: So I remember the lady looking at me saying, Bandra? Bangal? Bandra is a Bangal.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:23.000
[Guest]: So that kind of was the kind of transition that happened. But I find Noida particularly interesting.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
[Guest]: And so I think I've given you a very, very long answer, a very rambling answer.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:33.000
[Guest]: But it kind of gives you a perspective, a listener's perspective of me and I'll probably stop here.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a delightful answer with many strands I want to follow because long, I mean, our lives are long and rambling.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Amit Varma]: So how could, you know, why should we sort of simplify them? Otherwise, struck by a number of strands.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
[Amit Varma]: One is you kind of, you know, mentioned at the start that you grew up in Goa.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And the Goa where you studied was very different from Goa of the beaches.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, in the years that I was a professional poker player, I used to spend tons of time in the offshore casinos.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, all my friends would see that I am in Goa all the time.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And I would tell them that, listen, in these last four years, I haven't been to a beach even once.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Because it's a whole different sort of a city.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, one of the things that I was struck by, and this is something that's clear through all your writing,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:23.000
[Amit Varma]: is your intellectual curiosity, that you are always bringing wider frames to bear on in ways that we don't often think of them,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
[Amit Varma]: which I found extremely fascinating.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So here's a sort of broader question I had for later, but since the subject comes up now, I'll ask it.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:37.000
[Amit Varma]: I've kind of noticed that some of the most insightful people on social media that I've come across,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:44.000
[Amit Varma]: there's of course you in India, for example, but also, you know, people like Paul Graham, who started Y Combinator, and so on.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Some of the finest insights I have seen have come from venture capitalists or successful entrepreneurs

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Amit Varma]: who then gone on to, you know, fund other businesses and all of that.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And what struck me was that one, I should not be surprised that VCs are more insightful than others,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:08.000
[Amit Varma]: because their experience requires them to just look at a variety of businesses from a variety of perspectives

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and really, you know, understand people and understand society.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.000
[Amit Varma]: But also, there might be some selection bias at play because the people who make for good VCs to begin with,

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.000
[Amit Varma]: or choose that as a career track, might be people who already have those kind of broad lenses,

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and therefore are suited to being VCs and so on.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
[Amit Varma]: So, where do you see yourself in that spectrum?

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it would seem to me that since you've, you know, become a VC pretty late,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:39.000
[Amit Varma]: you are already someone who had those sort of broad worldviews, which made you a perfect fit.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But is there something to saying that it can also work the other way?

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And is there a sort of an optimal mentality, therefore, that a VC should have or a prospective VC should have?

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
[Guest]: Well, it's an interesting question. Many facets to that question.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Guest]: Firstly, I'll say that there aren't many successful VCs who write and who have interesting worldviews.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:07.000
[Guest]: But there are also equally very successful VCs who don't write anything, who don't necessarily express it.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:13.000
[Guest]: And so it is a business which success here can be reduced to a simple heuristic.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Guest]: But there is a strand of VC and the one reason why VCs do that is to compete for founders.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Guest]: So, the one reason I write is to build a personal brand, a personal brand that I hope help brings me to the notice of founders.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest]: And when they are looking to kind of talk to someone, when they're looking to kind of raise their own,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
[Guest]: I hope they will reach out to me via an email.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest]: So, this perspective is important and this kind of explains to a lot of this.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:49.000
[Guest]: So, it is true that VCs are generally interesting, there is huge intellectual curiosity, there is no doubt about that.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: That I think is the Sankar norm of becoming a VC.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
[Guest]: If you don't have that, it's very hard. It is both a necessary and a sufficient condition.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: To express that intellectual curiosity through writing, then you are fundamentally competing in the kind of an intellectual marketplace for ideas.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest]: And the way it works is the top, so in venture capital, typically in a fund and let's say in Bloom,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
[Guest]: there is a 100 million dollar fund and we invest in 25 to 27 companies.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:23.000
[Guest]: Of those 25 to 27 companies, invariably it is 3 to 4 of them that will kind of return most of our money.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:29.000
[Guest]: They bring in like 300 percent or 400 percent of the money and the rest just lose everything that we put in or almost there.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: I mean, kind of being very simplistic, so there is a power law to it.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Guest]: And fundamentally, the top 3 or 4 companies are led by great founders.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
[Guest]: And of course, you are trying to kind of get the best founders to pick you as much.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: So, unlike a lot of people feel that VCs pick founders, in the best deals, the founders are picking the VCs they want to work with.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: Because there is so much competition.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
[Guest]: Look back at all the big deals that happened, Facebook, etc.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
[Guest]: Mark Zuckerberg decided who is going to come in.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
[Guest]: And pretty much once in the top companies, the founders are doing the picking.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.000
[Guest]: Like Kunal Shah of Grit, who I think if you have not had him on the show, you should have him on the show.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[Guest]: So, Kunal Shah pretty much could have picked anyone.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
[Guest]: And he picked Sequoia, for example, for multiple reasons.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest]: So, VCs are competing for attention of founders through interesting world views and through interesting insights.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:17.000
[Guest]: And they hope the founders will notice.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:25.000
[Guest]: So, I belong to that one strand of that VC who is the content writer, the person who is trying to give out insights, etc.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
[Guest]: That is kind of one answer to one of the facets of your one.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:37.000
[Guest]: I do believe that, historically, VC used to be much more of a financial kind of world.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest]: In the sense that, typically, people who are strong in finance and are strong in technical, like semiconductors, etc.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
[Guest]: would typically find their way into it.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
[Guest]: Typically, the bridge of the two.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:55.000
[Guest]: But increasingly, we're beginning to see very diverse perspectives and you're beginning to see very interesting people make their way into VC.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
[Guest]: So, VC is getting democratized to that extent.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
[Guest]: So, I don't know if I kind of gave you the exact answer that you're looking for.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
[Guest]: But, yeah, so there we are.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that kind of makes sense.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the sort of, I had, for example, Santosh Desai and also Ambi Parmeswaran later at different points on my show.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things about both of them is that, you know, in their quest to become excellent at what they do, which is advertising,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Amit Varma]: they also came up with some surprisingly startling insights, at least to me, about Indian society.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And while reading some of your work, I came across some of those moments also.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Of course, the segmentation that you've done of India 1 Alpha, India 1, India 2, India 3, we'll discuss that in detail later.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But just one that kind of struck me was that in one of your essays, you have these three photographs of Starbucks in three countries.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And in the other two countries, which you pointed out, the menus are in the local language.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And in the particular, the third one, which is India, it's completely in English, where you point out that, you know, that there is like a separate class of people.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:08.000
[Amit Varma]: You've called them Anglo-Indians, you've called them India 1 Alpha, whatever, who are just completely apart from the rest of the country in a sense.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned Kunal Shah, I think he's referred to the same phenomenon in different words in a recent essay he wrote that got a fair bit of attention,

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
[Amit Varma]: pointing out that, you know, CRED was targeting that sort of segment as well.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.000
[Amit Varma]: So the way I want to have this conversation is that, of course, I want to talk about the Indian startup scene and the way it's evolved.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And you wrote this incredible 7000 word essay on that, which I'll link from the show notes.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Plus, I also want to talk about how venture capital firms work in India and how you see the current scenario and all of that.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: We'll talk about all of that. But I want to go back to your personal journey a little bit because you're basically the same age as me, right?

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:48.000
[Amit Varma]: We're both in our 40s. And, you know, we've kind of grown up through that very interesting period when one is intellectually curious,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
[Amit Varma]: but there is a limit to how much information you take in.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And like you pointed out, maybe working in the times of India is an interesting step because you're meeting, you know,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Amit Varma]: people with different kinds of specializations in the corridors and having those water cooler conversations.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And then one day, everything just explodes open, like the whole world of information is at your fingertips.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And so what was that sort of process like in a dual way?

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:19.000
[Amit Varma]: One, from making sense of the country as it was changing and evolving very rapidly through the late 90s and onwards.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And two, from a sense of your own personal growth as you begin to evolve the frames through which you look at the world,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:35.000
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, between then and now, is it possible for you to sort of pick those aha moments which kind of changed the way you look at everything?

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:44.000
[Guest]: That's a hard one. I don't know if there were specific aha moments. But yeah, like, so clearly, I'm a big beneficiary of liberalization.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:53.000
[Guest]: What happened in 91, 92, certainly had a big role to play, even though I graduated like six years later,

00:15:53.000 --> 00:16:00.000
[Guest]: because the economy had opened up and there was a lot more consumer spending beginning to kind of,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
[Guest]: if you unlike versus like the 70s where it was relatively more socialist.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: So certainly that was a big kind of a tailwind to my life.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Guest]: Joining Times, of course, and I was fortunate to get to work with Sameer Jain,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:23.000
[Guest]: the incredibly maverick, eccentric owner of the group. And I sort of became one of his EAs.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: And every time he used to come to Bombay, he used to come to Bombay in winters because Delhi pollution, etc.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: He used to call for me and my bosses would make me drop whatever I was doing and say, OK, you can manage it. Let's go.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:43.000
[Guest]: And I think I owe a lot to him in the sense that he's a fascinating personality and a lot of the conversation, a lot of the insights.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:49.000
[Guest]: So that certainly helped. So he was a big influence as well, even though, of course, you do move on now.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:58.000
[Guest]: And the next was, I think, in the early 2010s, I tried to start to write and I started newsletters, etc.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: And I think I was trying to kind of distill the world, so to say.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: And I think it came out of a and generally I felt that I was getting left behind.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Guest]: And I kind of compared myself to, you know, it's mid 30s, sort of maybe had male menopause early.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: Like you have these existential things. What am I doing? I'm not earning as well as my friends, etc.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:28.000
[Guest]: And I kind of got the sense at that point that increasingly, and I don't know if it came out of a specific article,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest]: that I felt like I needed to take greater control of my destiny and I sort of needed to.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:41.000
[Guest]: And so sort of like 37, 38, I started writing a lot more and kind of set up a website.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.000
[Guest]: I started writing, I tried newsletters, I did multiple things.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: But I mean, effectively every month or so, one or two articles would come out and that helped, I think.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
[Guest]: So these were certainly arcs to my life, so to say.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Guest]: And sort of if you kind of look to a lot of the hits that I've had have really come in the last two, three years.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest]: I mean, the first 60, 70 pieces I wrote, I mean, I don't think 10 people read each of those.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: And I would send it to people and I'm sure none of them touched it.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest]: They would say very nice, very nice.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
[Guest]: So I think a bunch of this certainly informed my worldview.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest]: And the more you try to write, the more you distill, etc. That certainly helps.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: So I think, again, so these are kind of the arcs or the tailwinds that have kind of propelled my life forward, so to say.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:33.000
[Guest]: Which finally led to Kartik Reddy reaching out, etc. And which kind of brought me here.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Did you feel the writing helped your thinking?

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Like I often, for example, in my writing class, which you participated in, in fact, I did talk about Orwell's conception of how it is not just the case that a clear thinker is more likely to write clearly.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But it is also the case that forcing yourself to write clearly helps you think better.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Was that kind of the case with you, that did you become a different person because you forced yourself to write so much?

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: Absolutely. I think that's so true. I don't think I have that quote readily in mind.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: Now that you've mentioned it, I'll go back and research it and keep it.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Guest]: I do think that writing, I mean, writing of a certain kind of quality does help your thinking.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Guest]: So, in Amitabh, there was a very interesting course. And if you actually go and talk to all the IMA guys, they actually talk to you about this course called WAC, Written Analysis and Communication.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
[Guest]: All it teaches you and you actually get grades for that. It's very simple.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Guest]: The trick is that each sentence has to be connected to the previous sentence and that's all.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:34.000
[Guest]: You can actually kind of the writing can be infelicitous, right?

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Guest]: It can be very poor. And what surprises you that the people who write the most flowery prose get the lowest grades.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
[Guest]: And then very quickly you need to go and work out, talk to them what happened.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: And you look at patterns in any sense that it actually doesn't matter.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:50.000
[Guest]: You can write in telegraphies, but each sentence has to just connect to that.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:58.000
[Guest]: So that's the first time I kind of felt that thinking, because structured thinking and structured writing seem to be linked.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:08.000
[Guest]: And certainly in the mid-2010s, I started writing. I could actually see that better writing helped because there is writing which is persuasive.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.000
[Guest]: There's also writing that is analytical. And when you do analytical writing, you're trying to break things down, etc.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: Certainly it helps. Writing is hard. It's painful. And I think writing is, so to say, but thinking is even harder.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:30.000
[Guest]: So writing is the medium in which you can do thinking. It's an easier medium than just pure thinking.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:39.000
[Guest]: So I kind of envy and I'm kind of scared by mathematicians because they have no medium other than like pure thinking.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.000
[Guest]: Right. That must be really hard. Or maybe even coding. I don't know.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:47.000
[Guest]: But writing is a much more comfortable medium in which you can express your thinking.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:53.000
[Guest]: And I've taken huge advantage of that. And even now when folks tell me that I want to talk to you for 15 minutes,

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:59.000
[Guest]: I just tell them, please write out what you want to. And I have the standard default things I send them.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.000
[Guest]: I find that typically writing it out helps you get more clarity.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest]: And typically they always turn back and say, hey, thank you for making me do that.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:12.000
[Guest]: So I totally agree with you. And thank you for that quote. I'm going to kind of file that for future.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'll send you a few more quotes like, you know, I've been adding slides on that theme to my course.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know if you were in an early batch, you might have missed it.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:25.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, Joan Didion talks about how she does her thinking by writing.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, Deirdre McCloskey, the great economist and author also wrote how writing was an essential part of that.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And just an aside for my readers, because this is something that I find myself having to repeat to more and more people,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.000
[Amit Varma]: is that what you said about, you know, that no one perhaps read your first 60 pieces.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And then it's only in the last couple of years that they've started becoming popular, strikes a chord.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things I notice among young people sometimes is that their approach is that they want to start doing something.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And if it doesn't work, they want to drop it. And I'm not sure that's a good approach.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:02.000
[Amit Varma]: My advice would be that if you love doing something, you've got to stick at it.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Because whenever we start doing anything, we will be bad at it.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, you cannot be good at anything from the get go.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's just by repeated iteration that you eventually achieve excellence, which is like a non-negotiable.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Like I remember this video by the YouTube productivity coach Ali Abdaal, a guy in his mid-20s.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:29.000
[Amit Varma]: An excellent video where he talks about, you know, he basically reached 1 million subscribers.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:35.000
[Amit Varma]: It took him a few years. But he said that at the end of the sixth month, he had made two videos a week.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And he reached exactly 1,000 subscribers on the day of the 50th video.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:45.000
[Amit Varma]: So if any of us was to, you know, hit that lack of response, we might be disheartened enough to give it up.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:47.000
[Amit Varma]: But he kept on and got to where he is.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And his advice was, if you're starting a YouTube channel, just make two videos a week for two years flat,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, 200 videos and only then look at the subscriber count, which frankly, I think is fantastic advice.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:06.000
[Amit Varma]: So I think people sometimes get, you know, and it's incredible that I'm actually saying this to a VC

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:12.000
[Amit Varma]: because typically VCs are considered to think in terms of where are the metrics and show me the progress and all of that.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
[Amit Varma]: But no, that's a stereotype. We'll get to that.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:19.000
[Amit Varma]: So since we were talking Ali Abdaal and productivity, I also want to ask about that.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things that strikes me is that in all your public-facing communication, you give your email ID out.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And you say, you actually invite people to write to you with ideas or thoughts or whatever that they might have.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And you tell them you'll respond to them soon.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And you've also elsewhere said that a VC like you has 12-hour days.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So, like, were you always someone who was very organized in terms of work?

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Or did you have to put a thought into how do I become more productive?

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Because it's something I personally struggle with. So I'm very fascinated by how you managed.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:52.000
[Guest]: Yeah, no, it's a great question. I'm going to enjoy answering this.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:58.000
[Guest]: Because one thing with VCs, other than curiosities or obsession with productivity hacks,

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:05.000
[Guest]: because every VC, early-stage VCs especially, and so sort of early-stage VCs struggle with what's called deal flow.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:11.000
[Guest]: Everybody is trying to reach out to them. Everybody wants 15 minutes. And everybody is like, etc.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:17.000
[Guest]: So it is challenging. And I must tell you that it just hit me head on.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:24.000
[Guest]: I did kind of before entering VC, I was actually, I think, had this huge anthropological interest in VC.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.000
[Guest]: And a lot of people used to actually tell me that, hey, how come you're not in VC?

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:32.000
[Guest]: 17, 16, I used to get this. Oh, aren't you there? I thought you were there.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:36.000
[Guest]: But still, it didn't prepare me for this kind of enormous assault on my time.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.000
[Guest]: So typically, you know, email is one challenge. You'll end up going to email.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:45.000
[Guest]: These days, WhatsApp. And you do stuff like time boxing.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:49.000
[Guest]: That's what it's called, where you have specific hours of the week.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:56.000
[Guest]: But, hey, not everything goes according to plan. And I do stuff like, today I knew that there were four things I had to do.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:02.000
[Guest]: One of which was to send you a particular email, which didn't get done by 12 or 2 or something, but it got done.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.000
[Guest]: So you need to have a very clear idea of the five things you want to do, four, three or four things you want to do.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
[Guest]: But other than that, I think, you know, so you do also need to react a lot.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.000
[Guest]: And I think the best thing I've found is, the single best advice I've found,

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
[Guest]: and one that it's an advice, but at the same time, it's something that I also worked out myself,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
[Guest]: was that anything that you need to do, you need to calendarize it.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:31.000
[Guest]: And so that's what I do. I just calendarize everything. And if it doesn't get on the calendar, sadly, it will not get done.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:37.000
[Guest]: But the challenge is also that you also need to give some free time, time where people can reach you.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:43.000
[Guest]: Some serendipity happens. You can read what you want to. So I do plan for that as well.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:47.000
[Guest]: But it is tough. You have all the usual hacks. I have Alfred, for example.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:55.000
[Guest]: It's a life-altering software where with a brief touch, like, you know, for example, I've kind of a lot of templated emails.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: So, for example, if somebody writes to me and I have a bitly link for certain FAQs,

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:07.000
[Guest]: and I just type like, you know, exclamation BI and that just appears and I just send it off.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:12.000
[Guest]: So a lot of these hacks and different VCs have different things. VCs use SuperHuman, which is, again, a lot of templates.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:19.000
[Guest]: I have a lot of cool Gmail hacks, et cetera. So time hacking is what a lot of VCs do.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Guest]: You're trying to get more out of it. You're trying to read more.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: Interestingly, you must hear this and that I actually pay people.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:33.000
[Guest]: I have three freelancers I pay to transcribe podcasts so that I don't have to listen to it.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:43.000
[Guest]: I pay them like 200 rupees for 1,000 words. And typically a 50-minute podcast is like what, 6,000, 7,000 words.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: And I end up paying them, you know, like 1,500 to 2,000, 1,200 to 4,000.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:52.000
[Guest]: And I found that that's actually worth it. So I keep doing all of these.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest]: It also means that one thing you do lose is serendipity and you do need to plan for that.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:03.000
[Guest]: So that's a challenge. But I don't know if this helps, this answers.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:07.000
[Amit Varma]: No, it's fascinating. I'm going to try out Alfred. I haven't used it yet.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:11.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, that should be fun. And planning for serendipity is such a nice term also.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, one can sort of lose track of, you know, those free moments when pleasant accidents happen.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Amit Varma]: So before we sort of get to the startup space, tell me a bit about your time in media, for example.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.000
[Amit Varma]: What was that like? Because, you know, I've been a journalist for a long time as well, I used to be.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the things I've realized in all this time is that journalism has changed so completely.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And yet most mainstream organizations simply don't realize it, simply don't get it.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Amit Varma]: That especially over the last 10 years, people are filtering content and consuming content and discovering content in completely different ways.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And yet pretty much all media organizations are stuck in the same sort of ways of gathering information and disseminating information and all of that.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:00.000
[Amit Varma]: So what was your time in media like? How did you see that space kind of evolve?

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And what do you think of when you look at the Indian media ecosystem today?

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: So I worked in the Times late 90s, but 2002 was when I joined the Economic Times.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:21.000
[Guest]: I was in the music business before that. And so 2002 to I think late 2018, like, you know, 16 years.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:26.000
[Guest]: I saw Indian media and I worked for a long time in print.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:31.000
[Guest]: I did work in other divisions, but print was where and because Times of India made a lot of money from print.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:43.000
[Guest]: I do feel that Indian media is historically, I think, has systematically seen an ocean of talent, like the best and brightest.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:50.000
[Guest]: I mean, sort of a cliche again. I don't think they ever worked in media, so to say, but at least you had a fair amount of bright people coming in.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:57.000
[Guest]: But over the years, I think the quality of people coming in has historically not kind of been the same.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:03.000
[Guest]: The other one is that print specifically because the Times of India and because of English,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:10.000
[Guest]: typically the Indian newspapers, which were in English, historically got a huge advantage.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Guest]: And I remember coming in early 2000s, etc.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:21.000
[Guest]: Look at the Nabarath Times at that time had like one fourth or one third the reader base of the Times of India.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:28.000
[Guest]: But their ad revenue was like one twelfth. So the Times of India had a disproportionate English premium, so to say.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:35.000
[Guest]: So specifically, the media business was largely a monopoly business.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.000
[Guest]: And typically, that's when you end up making a lot more money.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:45.000
[Guest]: So they were fattened on the monopoly profits, the Times of India and all of that.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:52.000
[Guest]: And that kind of continued. What happened is I think a lot of folks in the Times of India groups saw the warning signs.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:30:02.000
[Guest]: There were enough notes, etc. In fact, it's very strange that 1996, I sort of discovered this old pamphlet or something like that belongs to 1996.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:06.000
[Guest]: In 1996, they were seeing the Internet and threat to print.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:16.000
[Guest]: But in the US, finally took the 2008 financial crisis to really kind of run down print. And in India, it took COVID.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: So I think, long story short, they were largely monopolies. They were not necessarily well run, hence.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:29.000
[Guest]: But that's fine. The Times of India's genius was to discover that monopoly and just milk it forward.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:33.000
[Guest]: The other ones weren't even as well run, the other parts of the business.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:39.000
[Guest]: But any one was reasonably well run because it became a monopoly and they exploited it.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.000
[Guest]: First under Peter Mukherjee and then under Uday Shankar.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:47.000
[Guest]: So, but over time, kind of all the bad habits set in.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:51.000
[Guest]: And what has happened now is that the print business got eviscerated.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:54.000
[Guest]: I'm hearing like horror stories from the Times, etc.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:59.000
[Guest]: So TV is a little better, but OTT is creating problems there too.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:05.000
[Guest]: So yeah, so can double click if you want into specific aspects, but sort of, yeah.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Double click into one aspect for me, like, you know, you're obviously someone, it's part of your job to kind of keep gazing into the future.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:16.000
[Amit Varma]: 10 years from now, how will we be consuming media?

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Because like you said, COVID has changed things, things were changing before this.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:26.000
[Amit Varma]: The whole sort of landscape is fragmenting and splintering and everything is changed completely.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Like what is a day 10 years later from now? How is one getting one's information?

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:34.000
[Amit Varma]: What does one mean when one talks of journalism or the media?

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:39.000
[Guest]: Yeah, 10 years is hard, but I can talk to you about a few trends we're seeing.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:44.000
[Guest]: So one trend is sort of the death of the rapper, so to say, or creation of new rappers.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.000
[Guest]: So for example, the newspaper is a rapper.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:55.000
[Guest]: The newspaper kind of said, look, we'll give you sports, I'll give you a kind of fashion, I'll give you cartoons, I'll give you everything.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:59.000
[Guest]: And the national news will wrap it up and get off the scene.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:07.000
[Guest]: So like, for example, if you actually now go back and look at Esquire or GQ, it's a strange compunction.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:11.000
[Guest]: They have this fantastic three or four stories, which are like incredibly well written.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:18.000
[Guest]: It takes six months to produce. They pay the writer like $25,000, $30,000 just to, and also to travel, that's extra.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:23.000
[Guest]: What is it doing there? And it's free. And I read every one of those stories free.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:30.000
[Guest]: And of course, that's because there was a subscription base, which kind of meant an ad rate, and so on.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:36.000
[Guest]: But as the business declines, as advertising flees, the rappers don't make sense anymore.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:43.000
[Guest]: So what you've seen over the last few years is the rapper kind of breaking up and stories unbundled.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:50.000
[Guest]: So today, you can, for example, you see something on Twitter, you click on it, you go to some site.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:55.000
[Guest]: After I come out of the site and you ask me, hey, Sajith, where do you read this? I don't even know.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:04.000
[Guest]: So you don't even remember. So certainly a relationship with the writer, and that is what leads to Substack.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:08.000
[Guest]: So people are saying that people follow writers and people don't follow magazines.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:14.000
[Guest]: And that makes sense. But they're also very interesting. So OneTrend and Substack is like the new magazine.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:23.000
[Guest]: So there's a very interesting protocol called Every, E-V-R-Y. They've got a collective of writers and journalists who are making a new magazine.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
[Unknown]: So the joke that goes is, hey, they've discovered a magazine.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:34.000
[Guest]: So thanks to the Internet, we are kind of bundling and unbundling to make sense of the world.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:46.000
[Guest]: So certainly, I feel, but the fundamental thing is that people are going to kind of, the written word, people are going to kind of consume in,

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:52.000
[Guest]: so to say, the basic unit will be the writer. We're certainly seeing the death of gatekeepers.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:58.000
[Guest]: So again, you know about the tech versus media battle that's going on, Balaji versus everyone, you know.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: Yeah, it's great fun. So increasingly, and there have been interesting kind of brands like Oh My News, I think, that's what's called in Korea,

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.000
[Guest]: it's about citizen journalism. So we're going to kind of see more and more kind of vehicles,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: which kind of make more and more of us writers and producers, not necessarily text, but it could be multiple things.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:26.000
[Guest]: And that's a trend we're seeing as well, more and more creators and without editorial gatekeepers.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:33.000
[Guest]: And if you look at TikTok, if you look at in India, Chingari or Josh or whatever you call it, you're really seeing those folks.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:39.000
[Guest]: I also feel that I think it's called the Gutenberg parenthesis or there's maybe a better word.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:44.000
[Guest]: But the fact that historically, we're all about orality, a culture of orality.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:51.000
[Guest]: But Gutenberg meant that we became word first. And so we're likely to see a lot more innovation.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:57.000
[Guest]: And Clubhouse is one, like, you know, but there'll be many more around audiovisual media.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest]: So sort of what McLuhan said, and he's an interesting one to look at, the shift from hot to cold.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.000
[Guest]: So we're actually going to see a lot more cold communication.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:15.000
[Guest]: And if hot, print is largely hot because there's no context loss when you read print.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:20.000
[Guest]: But we're going to see a lot more kind of stuff in memes and cartoons.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:26.000
[Guest]: And if you look at it, the most critical part of the Times of India is Sandeep Adwaryu, the cartoonist,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:35.000
[Guest]: because and that's where today to actually see what the journalists think and what the liberal folks at Times think,

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:40.000
[Guest]: go to his cartoonist son on Twitter and see what he is. It is brutal.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:45.000
[Guest]: But the entire Times of India, the way it reads, because the owners are looking at it, it's very tame.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:53.000
[Guest]: So today, as we kind of enter this really strange world, I think a lot more communication is going to go to memes.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:58.000
[Guest]: It's going to go to cartoons and stuff like that, as opposed to the word,

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.000
[Guest]: which can be actually reduced to something very cold and people can actually poke holes.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:08.000
[Guest]: So this is sort of what kind of feel I can give you more trends, but to probably summarize,

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:15.000
[Guest]: oral, memes, the wrapper being broken up and maybe rewrapped. Yeah.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, that's fascinating. And just kind of thinking aloud from sort of my own learnings over the past few months,

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, on the one hand, there is, it's very hopeful that the creator economy has bloomed,

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:30.000
[Amit Varma]: that creators no longer have to depend on platforms or advertising and they can reach readers directly.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And Substack is, of course, one way of doing that. And you can reach what Kevin Kelly called your thousand true fans.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, the flip side of it is that that's true for creators who've sort of, you know,

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:48.000
[Amit Varma]: who in a sense are the top 1% of creators, people who've kind of built a brand for themselves,

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
[Amit Varma]: even someone like me that I'm fortunate to be in a position after all these years,

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:54.000
[Amit Varma]: where I have the kind of brand that I can, you know, monetize that a little bit.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm thinking of the young people starting out and the average person who is discovering news.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, from the point of view of the young person starting out, at least for all its flaws,

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:08.000
[Amit Varma]: what the earlier system gave them was that there was an institution where you could join,

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:12.000
[Amit Varma]: where you could imbibe certain values that this is how you do editing,

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:17.000
[Amit Varma]: and this is how you do fact checking and all of that, and this is how you do reporting and all of that.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And there is that institutional structure which gives them all of that,

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:26.000
[Amit Varma]: which seems to me to be a good thing because then there is a structured way in which they can grow

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:30.000
[Amit Varma]: rather than necessarily have to be self-motivated and find their own way.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Because the incentives of being a creator who nobody knows is that you have to do things to somehow get noticed

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:43.000
[Amit Varma]: and to stand out and those might not necessarily be the best incentives towards personal intellectual growth.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other aspect of it is that, you know, in the sense that earlier there was a consensus of the truth.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:54.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, you read every day, the Times of India is coming to your home or the New York Times,

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:58.000
[Amit Varma]: depending on where you are. And, you know, it might have one slant or the other,

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:04.000
[Amit Varma]: NYT might be slightly left, WSJ might be slightly right, and both of them were only that on their opinion pages.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:09.000
[Amit Varma]: The reporting has, you know, certain standards and there is a broad consensus on the truth.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Today, there's nothing. Today, it's you believe whatever narrative you want.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: All your information is through discrete links on social media.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, we've seen the worst of Twitter, but, you know,

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:25.000
[Amit Varma]: whatever I hear about these alternative WhatsApp universes is completely crazy.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And like you've pointed out in one of your very insightful comments that you've made on this YouTube talk you gave,

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:34.000
[Amit Varma]: which I was watching, where you divided India 1, India 2, India 3,

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:40.000
[Amit Varma]: and you pointed out that none of these apps or businesses that we recognize are actually reaching India 3,

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:44.000
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, more than a billion people, which you equated to sub-Saharan Africa.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:49.000
[Amit Varma]: But WhatsApp is there because they cater to the most basic need of simple communication,

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:56.000
[Amit Varma]: which is also kind of scary in a sense that, you know, WhatsApp is basically the biggest.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:04.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they're obviously not a media house, but effectively it's the biggest source of media for everybody kind of in the country.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:09.000
[Amit Varma]: But this is just a ramble. I was just kind of responding to you. I don't know if you have anything to say to this.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:12.000
[Guest]: No, I probably didn't double click on it.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:19.000
[Guest]: But the point I think I want to say is, I think historically we got the wrappers we didn't select.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:26.000
[Unknown]: W-R-A-P-P-E-R-S, not R-A-P-P-E-R-S.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:30.000
[Guest]: So today you can actually wrap it in the way you want.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:37.000
[Guest]: And that's scary because certainly there is the splinter net today. I don't think there's any doubt on that.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:43.000
[Guest]: It's very hard. And I actually do try and follow people of different persuasions.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:50.000
[Guest]: I didn't want to kind of be cocooned. So I do follow people who I wouldn't probably spend an evening with on Twitter.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:54.000
[Guest]: But I don't see very many people doing that. It's hard.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: So I do think that there's no doubt about it, that we are splintering and people are selecting the media that they want to consume.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Guest]: I don't think there's an easy solution here. Historically, I think the U.S. kind of platforms, largely U.S.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:16.000
[Guest]: but also China, have kind of said, look, it's user-generated content.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:19.000
[Guest]: And the Section 230, which says we're not responsible for it, etc.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:31.000
[Guest]: But I think that kind of works in a context where, you know, it's a country where they've had their first amendment in the 19th century

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:39.000
[Guest]: was about freedom of speech, whereas our First Amendment was actually curtailing the freedom of speech in the 1950s, etc.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:45.000
[Guest]: So they're very different countries and they have the institutions which can kind of handle this.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:52.000
[Guest]: But we don't have those institutions. Right. And which is why WhatsApp, for example, actually had to kind of create friction in its product.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:56.000
[Guest]: If you actually see in the U.S., you can actually forward it to multiple people.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:03.000
[Guest]: Whereas in India and some other countries like maybe in Africa, because of how rumors can spread, you can only forward it to five people.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:08.000
[Guest]: So the first time when a product had to go back and change features to create friction.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:15.000
[Guest]: So and there is this joke that I say that, hey, all of these platforms said user-generated content, we don't need editors.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:22.000
[Guest]: But hey, all the editors that you lost in user-generated content, you spend on the moderators that you need now.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:28.000
[Guest]: Like, you know, and TikTok has some 40,000 moderators apparently, you know, filtering out in China.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:34.000
[Guest]: It's going to do in there everything from child porn or whatever it is to, you know, references to Tiananmen or whatever.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:39.000
[Guest]: So I think these trends are there and I don't think there are easy answers.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:46.000
[Guest]: And you can actually see some of those tensions come to light. Yeah. So, yeah. And one ramble to your ramble.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I know this is a show of rambles as it were. And of course, you won't be listening to this episode.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:57.000
[Amit Varma]: You'll be reading it once you get it transcribed, which is fascinating.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other thought that strikes me, and again, just to ramble, I mean, you mentioned tech versus the tech media war, which is kind of happening.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And there I'm completely on the side of the tech guys, because it seems to me that the big media there which covers tech does not get it at all.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:14.000
[Amit Varma]: They are completely clueless. And there's a word for this particular syndrome.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:19.000
[Amit Varma]: I've forgotten what it is. Maybe you know it, but I think it's a three word term.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And the last one is amnesia, where essentially what happens is that when you read a media story on something on a subject that you know a lot about,

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:31.000
[Amit Varma]: you realize how bad it is because it is, of course, written by a generalist.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Amit Varma]: But when you read everything else in the newspaper and subjects you don't know about, you assume that it is the truth.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:46.000
[Amit Varma]: It is a word of God, you know, without realizing that if these generalists have so badly messed up a subject that you know so well, then chances are they've messed up everything.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And from whatever subjects that I might know, you know, whenever I read media coverage of that, whether it's, you know, poker or podcasting or whatever.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:43:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And I'm like, oh, my God, you know, and at least an honest journalist will get a lot of quotes from specialists and, you know, will not try to make too many assumptions themselves.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, it is so messy. And the delightful thing about, you know, what the internet did was that it made so many specialists available to us.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So we don't have to listen to these generalists. We can just go straight to this specialist and therefore have someone like you explain the VC business to us instead of some random journalist who's researched it for two hours.

